row.” Unlike the Jim Crow era where ideas about innate racial inferiority and superiority were the grounds for segregation, Hollywood’s version tries to use economic and cultural explanations to justify the underrepresentation and stigmatization of Black filmmakers. Erigha exposes the key elements at work in maintaining Hollywood’s racial hierarchy, namely the relationship between genre and race, the ghettoization of Black directors to black films, and how Blackness is perceived by the Hollywood producers and studios who decide what gets made and who gets to make it. Erigha questions the notion that increased representation of African Americans behind the camera is the sole answer to the racial inequality gap. Instead, she suggests focusing on the obstacles to integration for African American film directors. Hollywood movies have an expansive reach and exert tremendous power in the national and global production, distribution, and exhibition of popular culture. The Hollywood Jim Crow fully dissects the racial inequality embedded in this industry, looking at alternative ways for African Americans to find success in Hollywood and suggesting how they can band together to forge their own career paths.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAfrican American motion picture producers and directors. 0aAfrican Americans in the motion picture industry. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aBlack.  aHollywood.  aOscars.  aW. E. B. Du Bois.  aaudience.  acinema.  acollective.  aculture.  adirectors.  adistribution.  aeconomic.  afilm.  aforeign market.  afranchise.  agenre.  aghetto.  ainequality.  aliberal.  amedia.  aproduction budgets.  arace.  aracial bias.  aracial hierarchy. 